# Assuming future_predictions contains the predicted number of sets,
# and the last year is 2030 (or the last year of your prediction)

# Load necessary library
library(flexdashboard)

# Get the prediction for the last year
last_year_prediction <- tail(future_predictions, 1)$num_parts

# Define the maximum value for the gauge, which should be more than the highest prediction
max_value <- max(future_predictions$num_parts) * 1.1  # Adjust this based on your data

# Create a gauge
gauge(
  value = last_year_prediction,
  min = 0,
  max = max_value,
  symbol = ' sets',
  gaugeSectors(
    success = c(0, max_value * 0.6), 
    warning = c(max_value * 0.6, max_value * 0.8), 
    danger = c(max_value * 0.8, max_value)
  )
)

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.
